<subSubSection id="4F9065400633092BFF61FECCFC37FB98" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FECCFCF0FE6D" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFF61FECCFE85FE80" bold="true" box="[199,345,295,320]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus id="D83188690633092BFEC3FECCFE11FE80" box="[357,461,295,320]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Holotype</typeStatus>
posteriorly incomplete, broken into three parts, 
<quantity id="C0729B2E0633092BFBB2FEC3FBB5FEFF" box="[1044,1129,296,320]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="C0729B2E0633092BFB1DFEC3FADEFEFF" box="[1211,1282,296,320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
wide for 50 setigerous segments; 10 thoracic setigers. Specimen from Sta. PS-61, 46-3 complete, 
<quantity id="C0729B2E0633092BFBE9FEA7FB42FEA4" box="[1103,1182,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="19.0">19 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="C0729B2E0633092BFB45FEA7FAE5FEA4" box="[1251,1337,332,356]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
wide for 80 setigers; with 11 thoracic setigers. Specimen from Sta. PS-67, 110-11 smaller, complete, in two parts, 
<quantity id="C0729B2E0633092BFAFFFE9BFA41FE47" box="[1369,1437,368,391]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="7.0">7 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity id="C0729B2E0633092BFF71FE7FFEF1FE6C" box="[215,301,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.4">0.4 mm</quantity>
wide for 40 setigers; with 9 thoracic setigers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FE5CFCA8FDFC" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Thoracic region widest part of body, with 9â€“11 setigers, rounded in cross section, not depressed (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFA81FE5CFAA7FE10" box="[1319,1403,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
B). Transition between thorax and abdomen abrupt (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFD1AFE37FCD0FE34" box="[700,780,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
A) or with one transitional segment. Abdominal segments becoming narrow in posterior one-third of body. Branchiae from setiger 18â€“21, small and stubby at first, becoming thin, about twice as long as notopodial postsetal lobes (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFCA7FDCFFC8EFDFC" box="[769,850,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FDACFB90FD44" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Prostomium conical, pointed; no eyespots (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFD15FDACFCCCFDA0" box="[691,784,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 17</figureCitation>
A, 18A); nuchal organs as large slit between prostomium and peristomium (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFEC5FD87FE69FD44" box="[355,437,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="37.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[161,1429,204,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[151,1436,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Weddell Sea, ANDEEP I ANT XIX- 3, R / V Polarstern, Sta. PS- 61 / 046 - 3 (SEM, JAB). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, Anterior end, left lateral view; prostomium, peristomium, and location of nuchal organ; C, middle abdominal segments, dorsal view; D, abdominal parapodium, anterior view; E, thoracic capillary setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245844/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
B). Peristomium with one achaetous ring (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFC28FD87FC35FD44" box="[910,1001,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 17</figureCitation>
A, 18A).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FD64FCBFFC9D" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Thoracic segments all similar, with prominent postsetal lobes; notopodial postsetal lobes subtriangular (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFAC9FD64FF69FD0C" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
B); neuropodial postsetal lobe arising from low postsetal ridge (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFC02FD5FFC27FD0C" box="[932,1019,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
B). Middle and posterior abdominal parapodia dorsally elevated; elevated parapodia fused across dorsum, forming raised dorsal crest from which branchiae arise, best observed in posterior abdominal segments (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFC2CFD17FC03FCD4" box="[906,991,764,789]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="37.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[161,1429,204,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[151,1436,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Weddell Sea, ANDEEP I ANT XIX- 3, R / V Polarstern, Sta. PS- 61 / 046 - 3 (SEM, JAB). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, Anterior end, left lateral view; prostomium, peristomium, and location of nuchal organ; C, middle abdominal segments, dorsal view; D, abdominal parapodium, anterior view; E, thoracic capillary setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245844/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
C). Abdominal notopodia with narrow fingerlike postsetal lobe (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFE60FCF4FDF4FCF8" box="[454,552,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Figs. 17</figureCitation>
C, 18D); neuropodia elongated, apically expanded, divided into two lobes between which setae arise (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFE6CFCAFFDC7FC9C" box="[458,539,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
C); without subpodial flange.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FC8CFECFFC64" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Branchiae short at first (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFE79FC8CFDECFC40" box="[479,560,871,896]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="37.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[161,1429,204,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[151,1436,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Weddell Sea, ANDEEP I ANT XIX- 3, R / V Polarstern, Sta. PS- 61 / 046 - 3 (SEM, JAB). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, Anterior end, left lateral view; prostomium, peristomium, and location of nuchal organ; C, middle abdominal segments, dorsal view; D, abdominal parapodium, anterior view; E, thoracic capillary setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245844/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
Câ€“D), then becoming longer than notopodial lobes in far posterior segments (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFF39FC67FF2DFC64" box="[159,241,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FC44FC37FB98" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Thoracic setae all crenulated capillaries (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFD0DFC44FCDDFC08" box="[683,769,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="37.[151,249,1914,1936]" captionTargetBox="[161,1429,204,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[151,1436,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 18. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Weddell Sea, ANDEEP I ANT XIX- 3, R / V Polarstern, Sta. PS- 61 / 046 - 3 (SEM, JAB). A, anterior end, dorsal view; B, Anterior end, left lateral view; prostomium, peristomium, and location of nuchal organ; C, middle abdominal segments, dorsal view; D, abdominal parapodium, anterior view; E, thoracic capillary setae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245844/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
E); notopodial fascicles with 6â€“8 setae; neurosetae more numerous, arranged in two dense rows. Abdominal notopodia with 6â€“9 long capillaries and 3â€“4 furcate setae; each furcate seta with one tyne shorter than the other, both blunted on tips with apical notch; tynes connected by thin webbing composed of fine needles (
<figureCitation id="9FB12A4E0633092BFD9EFBF7FD50FBF4" box="[568,652,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1983,2005]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,210,1945]" captionTargetId="figure@36.[166,1418,195,1959]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 17. Leitoscoloplos rankini n. sp. Holotype (USNM 1013903). A, anterior end, right lateral view; B, thoracic parapodium, anterior view; C, posterior abdominal segment, posterior view; D, furcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/245843/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
D). Abdominal neuropodia with long and short capillaries; 1â€“2 very short and thin aciculae, sometimes protruding. Pygidium with two thin cirri.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4F9065400633092BFF61FB8FFD62FB05" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FB8FFD62FB05" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFF61FB8FFE92FBBD" bold="true" box="[199,334,1124,1149]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Etymology.</emphasis>
This species is named for the late Dr. John S. (Stubby) Rankin, Professor Emeritus of the University of 
<collectingRegion id="C54EF8290633092BFE98FB6CFE14FB60" box="[318,456,1159,1184]" country="United States of America" name="Connecticut" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Connecticut</collectingRegion>
, friend, and teacher. Dr. Rankin was director of the sampling program during the International Weddell Sea Expedition (
<date id="7334100B0633092BFDECFB47FD6EFB05" box="[586,690,1196,1221]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" value="1968" valueMax="1969">1968â€“69</date>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="4F9065400633092BFF61FB24FCB3FAB8" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="073536CB0633092BFF61FB24FCB3FAB8" blockId="38.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFF61FB24FEE7FB28" bold="true" box="[199,315,1231,1256]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="C08A4D480633092BFEE4FB3BFDE2FB28" box="[322,574,1232,1256]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Leitoscoloplos" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="rankini" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFEE4FB3BFDE2FB28" box="[322,574,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Leitoscoloplos rankini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFDE3FB24FD58FB28" bold="true" box="[581,644,1231,1256]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="2ECD57A20633092BFDE3FB24FD58FB28" box="[581,644,1231,1256]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is a deep-sea species belonging to the 
<taxonomicName id="C08A4D480633092BFB9CFB3AFB3EFB28" box="[1082,1250,1232,1256]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Leitoscoloplos" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="kerguelensis">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFB9CFB3AFB3EFB28" box="[1082,1250,1232,1256]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">L. kerguelensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group in having branchiae first present from the anterior abdominal region. The species differs from related forms in the nature of the inflated and elevated parapodia of the posterior abdominal segments. These parapodia are located on the posterior border of the segments and are elevated dorsally to form prominent crests. Further differences with related forms are discussed under 
<taxonomicName id="C08A4D480633092BFDB2FA8AFD46FAB8" box="[532,666,1376,1400]" class="Polychaeta" family="Orbiniidae" genus="Leitoscoloplos" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="eltaninae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFDB2FA8AFD46FAB8" box="[532,666,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">L. eltaninae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="35FEEAD90633092BFD07FAB4FD3CFAB8" bold="true" box="[673,736,1375,1400]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="2ECD57A20633092BFD07FAB4FD3CFAB8" box="[673,736,1375,1400]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(see above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
